doc.title: China Industrial Tech
doc.source_uri: 2025-09-02/2Q25 wrap_ Buoyant outlook in AIDC supply chain; downside surprise from PA; 3 rating changes_2025-09-02

passages.text: Our coverage companies all reported 1H25/2Q25 results which look in- line overall while we see the most buoyant 2H25- 2026E or even 2027E outlook in the AIDC supply chain (Envicool/Kstar/Kehua/Jianghai/Sungrow/Han's Laser) and the biggest downside surprise coming from process automation players (Baosight 2Q25 revenue/net profit \(- 35\% / - 63\%\) vs. GSe; and Supcon 2Q25 revenue/net profit \(- 14\% / - 40\%\) vs. GSe). Post the results, we fine tune our sector rating distribution by upgrading Han's Laser to Buy (PCB equipment upcycle of its Han's CNC subsidiary) and downgrading Supcon/Baosight to Neutral/Sell. Our defensive+Al approach (report link) still looks intact heading into the remaining part of the year.

In cooling infrastructure, the rapid growth of liquid cooling penetration in general- purpose and ASIC GPUs is creating opportunities for domestic cooling players within an ecosystem traditionally dominated by Taiwanese and U.S. players. Envicool is a prime example, with its liquid cooling products, including quick disconnects, manifolds, cold plates, coolants, and leakage detection, gaining recognition and seeing volume adoption by leading chipmakers and computing equipment manufacturing. Envicool reported robust server cooling and other sales growth of \(+216\%\) in 1H25. The company is actively recruiting and investing in Southeast Asia and the U.S., having founded a second subsidiary in Fremont, California, in May 2025, following an office in Houston, Texas, in August 2024. They are in co- R&D/commercialization stages with customers/end- users in multiple regions for different types of critical loads (general- purpose GPUs, ASIC AI chips, servers, switches etc.) and expect to see more meaningful sales contribution going
into late 2H25E and 2026E. We expect Envicoo to capture \(5\%\) of the global server liquid cooling market share by 2027E and \(10\%\) by 2030E.

Meanwhile, Sanhua has long been supplying liquid cooling components (valves, pumps, heat exchangers, CDUs) mostly to commercial HVAC customers with Rmb1bn+ sales in 2024 and further acceleration in 1H25, already reaching \(c.10\%\) global market share (GSe). AVIC Jonhon also doubled its revenue from the data center end- market in 1H25.

On power infrastructure, Kstar and Kehua are clear beneficiaries. They experienced solid data center capacity demand growth in China, with increasing wallet share opportunities among leading Chinese cloud and colocation customers. Both companies are also actively expanding their global footprint by capitalizing on surging data center investment in Southeast Asia and potentially engaging in Original Design Manufacturing (ODM) in the North American AIDC market to address capacity constraints of overseas players. Jianghai has confirmed EDLC orders from Meta. Technology upgrades are also attracting new entrants and capital, with Sungrow now developing a wide range of AIDC power products, including HVDC (800V), SST, PSU, and BBU, leveraging synergies with its power conversion technology. Sungrow aims to launch product samples next year, primarily targeting overseas markets. Separately, Han's Laser is seeing strong Printed Circuit Board (PCB) equipment demand from domestic PCB players expanding capacity for various AI hardware.

Share prices of Envicoo/Kstar/Kehua/Han's Laser/Jianghai/Sungrow/Sanhua- A/Sanhua- H/AVIC Jonhn have been up by \(99\% /60\% /37\% /30\% /40\% /39\% /21\% /19\% /10\%\) (vs. CSI300 at \(10\%\) ) in Aug 2025, and we probably need to see higher market share than our expectation to drive sustained outperformance ahead. We upgrade Han's Laser to Buy from Neutral on sales growth and margin turnaround driven by domestic PCB capacity expansion and equipment needs powered by AI applications and the upcoming smartphone industry form factor changes (e.g. foldable phones) leading to new consumer electronics equipment demand.
2) Humanoid Robots: Supply chain continues to reshape with patience needed for better visibility

LeaderDrive reported \~Rmb50mn humanoid robot revenue in 1H25 (equal to 4-5k units of robot), implying a likely dominant market share among robots adopting harmonic reduction gears. On the other hand, BEST did not show much meaningful progress nor financial contribution regarding its humanoid robot component business in 1H25, with management commenting that they are still engaging with different overseas/domestic customers.

Sanhua reiterated its conviction that humanoid robots represent the largest long- term AI application. Sanhua's Thailand factory is scheduled for volume production in 3Q25, with capacity commented as order- driven. The company guided stable market leadership in its humanoid robot actuators despite market concerns on supply chain uncertainty as its customer is still working on the robot redesign. We view the potential Tesla Optimus Gen 3 launch into end- 25E as a key event to watch.

Inovance, for example, is increasing its focus on humanoid robot components, developing a series of modularized and standardized products including low- voltage high- drives, frameless torque rotors, roller screws, and actuators, which are in various R&D and sampling stages. Notably, its roller screws are currently in the sampling stage.

We stay relatively cautious on China industrial automation demand, forecasting \(- 1\% / - 3\% / - 2\%\) yoy in 2025E/26E/27E. In the discrete automation industry, Inovance's comments on its 2H25E outlook exceeded our expectations, as the company guided for a better second half compared to the first half. This is likely due to company- specific factors, including continuous market share gains, better customer exposure, and overseas expansion (link). Conversely, Yiheda noted possible headwinds from lower consumer electronics capex demand, partly due to geopolitical uncertainties, and a deceleration in battery capacity expansion growth in 2H25E.

In the process automation industry, Baosight and Supcon saw sales decline and significant earnings decrease in 1H25, primarily attributed to the supply- demand imbalance and capacity contraction in the domestic steel and (petro)chemicals industries respectively. We downgrade Baosight to Sell from Neutral and Supcon to Neutral from Buy, given (1) the prolonged weakness of steel and (petro)chemicals capex will likely sustain in 2025- 27E based on GS China Macro and respective sector teams' forecasts, and (2) the new initiatives (robotics solutions and large PLC for Baosight; and industrial AI and subscription- based software for Supcon), albeit showing solid R&D and early commercialization progress, are still small in revenue scale and hence not enough to offset the traditional business downturn.

We continue to favor defensive names in addition to AI- related plays. We maintain a Buy rating on NARI Tech, a key beneficiary of China's structural shift in smart grid investment. NARI Tech delivered above- expectation revenue growth in 2Q25, with positive progress in overseas expansion, despite GPM pressure. Its overseas revenue grew by \(139\%\) yoy in 1H25, reaching Rmb1,987 million and accounting for \(8\%\) of firmwide revenue. Newly signed overseas contracts also increased by \(200\%\) yoy.

We also like AVIC Jonhon due to its stable aerospace and defense growth outlook, coupled with rising liquid cooling contributions. Furthermore, we prefer CRRC- H given its attractive dividend yield (4.5% 2026E dividend yield) among our coverage and a solid railway equipment delivery outlook for 2H25 and 2026. This outlook is supported by large- scale tendering in Multiple Units (MUs) and locomotives in July- August 2025. Year- to- date MU/locomotive tendering has reached 278 standard trainsets and 455 units, exceeding previous estimates of 230 standard trainsets and 400 units, providing concrete support for full- year earnings (link).

Post market close on Aug 29, AVIC Jonhon reported 2Q25 results, with revenue/gross profit/operating profit/net profit at Rmb6,345mn/2,016mn/917mn/797mn, \(+22\% / + 1\% / + 1\% / - 13\%\) yoy, \(+4\% / - 8\% / - 5\% / - 20\%\) vs GSe. GPM/OPM/NPM arrived at \(32\% /14\% /13\%\) , - 7pp/- 3pp/- 5pp yoy, \(+3pp / + 1pp / - 1pp\) qoq, - 4pp/- 1pp/- 4pp vs GSe. We view the fluctuations as normal seasonality and likely product mix reasons, and only minimally adjust our 2025- 30E EPS while keeping our 12- m TP unchanged at Rmb46.1. We maintain Buy given a solid defense spending growth outlook to support the national aerospace & defense informatization goal and rising liquid cooling contribution.
Exhibit 3:AVIC Jonhon forecast changes
Source: Company data, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

Raytron reported 2Q25 results with revenue/gross profit/EBIT/net profit recording Rmb1,407mn/768mn/283mn/205mn, \(+39\% / + 45\% / + 80\% / + 114\%\) yoy, \(+13\% / + 26\% / + 75\% / - 6\%\) vs GSe. GPM/OPM/NPM arrived at \(55\% /20\% /15\%\) in 2Q25, \(+2pp / + 5pp / + 5pp\) yoy, \(+6pp / + 7pp / - 3pp\) vs GSe. The results were in line with our expectations. We update for actual results with 2025- 30E EPS tweaked by 7- 12% and our new 12- m TP arrives at Rmb61.1 (from Rmb54.6), still based on 2026E P/E of 25X.
Exhibit 4: Raytron forecast changes
Source: Company data, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

Estun reported 2Q25 results with revenue/EBIT/net profit recording Rmb1,304mn/17mn/6mn, \(+12\% /n.m./n.m.yoy\) \(+12\% /n.m./n.m.vsGSe\) GPM/OPM/NPM arrived at \(27\% /1\% /0\%\) in 2Q25, \(+1\mathrm{pp} / + 6\mathrm{pp} / + 6\mathrm{pp}\) yoy, \(- 4\mathrm{pp} / + 2\mathrm{pp} / + 0\mathrm{pp}\) vs GSe. The topline slightly exceeded our expectation but was weaker than peer Inovance's 2Q25 revenue growth at \(19\%\) yoy and also significantly below Estun's 2Q25 industrial robot sales volume at \(+44\%\) yoy. The continuous deterioration of GPM indicates intensifying pricing competition in the industrial robot market. We update for actual results with 2025- 30E EPS revised by \(- 137\% \sim - 4\%\) with our 2025E revenue/net loss at Rmb4,711/- 26mn \((+18\% /n.m.yoy)\) , or \(4\% /132\%\) lower than Wind consensus. Our new 12- m TP arrives at Rmb9.5 (from Rmb9.9), still based on 2026E P/E of 35X. Maintain Sell.
Exhibit 5: Estun forecast changes
Source: Company data, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

Moons' Electric reported 2Q25 results with revenue/EBIT/net profit recording Rmb719mn/14mn/20mn, \(+10\% / - 48\% /41\%\) yoy, \(- 12\% / - 75\% / - 68\%\) vs GSe. GPM/OPM/NPM arrived at \(33\% /2\% /3\%\) in 2Q25, - 3pp/- 2pp/- 2pp yoy, - 5pp/- 5pp/- 5pp vs GSe. The 2Q25 topline underperformed FA peer companies Inovance/Yiheda of \(+19\% / + 22\%\) yoy and humanoid robot peer LeaderDrive of \(+30\%\) yoy. We see that the company faces intensifying pricing competition and is slower- than- peers in ramping- up in humanoid robot products. Therefore, we update for actual results with 2025E- 30E EPS revised by \(- 44\% \sim - 2\%\) with our 2025E revenue/net profit at Rmb2,614mn/298mn \((+8\% / + 68\%\) yoy), or \(- 1\% /11\%\) vs. Wind consensus. Our new 12- m TP arrives at Rmb48.7 (from Rmb49.8), still based on 2030E P/E of 37X discounted back to 2026E at a CoE of \(9.5\%\) . Maintain Neutral.
Exhibit 6: Moons'Electric forecast change
Source: Company data, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

Luster reported 2Q25 results with revenue/EBIT/net profit recording  Rmb754mn/33mn/81mn, \(+17\% / - 29\% / - 14\%\) yoy, \(- 3\% /n.m. / + 26\%\) vs GSe.  GPM/OPM/NPM arrived at \(36\% /4\% /11\%\) in 2Q25, - 5pp/- 3pp/- 4pp yoy, \(+1pp / + 0pp / + 2pp\) vs GSe. The Yuanke Fangzhou (including FZMotion Mocap business) revenue recorded \(+118\%\) yoy in 1H25 but still only account for \(2\%\) of total revenue. For the major machine vision business, the company's overall 2Q25 topline underperformed peer OPT at \(+40\%\) yoy. We update for actual results with 2025- 30E EPS revised by \(+7\% \sim +14\%\) to reflect margin improvement with our 2025E revenue/net profit at Rmb2,707mn/203mn \((+21\% / + 90\%\) yoy), or \(- 4\% / + 18\%\) vs. Wind consensus. Our new 12- m TP arrives at Rmb23.6 (from Rmb22.1), still based on 2026E P/E of 30X. Maintain Neutral.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
